-- ============================================================
-- FALSE POSITIVE REDUCTION
--
-- Some legitimate accounts may show high drain ratios:
--
-- 1. Business accounts paying suppliers same day
--    → Cross-reference with occupation and declared income
--      A restaurant owner paying Metro Cash & Carry = normal
--      A student sending funds to Nigeria = suspicious
--
-- 2. One-time salary received + rent paid same day
--    → Add counterparty filter: exclude known payees
--      AND t_out.counterparty NOT LIKE '%Landlord%'
--
-- 3. Inter-account transfers (savings, investment)
--    → Add tx_type filter:
--      AND t_out.tx_type != 'INTERNAL'
--
-- In production: combine velocity flag with:
--   - Counterparty jurisdiction risk
--   - Transaction type (CRYPTO = higher weight)
--   - Customer profile match (declared income vs volume)
--   - Pattern repetition (one-off vs recurring)
-- ============================================================


-- ============================================================
-- DIFFERENCE VS PASS-THROUGH DETECTION (Query #2)
--
-- Pass-Through (Query #2):
--   → Looks at the GLOBAL ratio over the entire period
--   → One row per customer
--   → Answers: "Is this account generally a transit point?"
--   → Best for: identifying money mule accounts overall
--
-- Velocity (Query #1):
--   → Looks at each INDIVIDUAL deposit
--   → One row per deposit
--   → Answers: "Was this specific deposit drained in 72h?"
--   → Best for: triggering real-time alerts per transaction
--
